---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import NewsletterCTA from '../components/NewsletterCTA.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="The engineer behind The Foundations of Software Engineering.">
  <article>
    <div class="wrap">
      <header class="post-hero">
        <span class="kicker post-kicker">About<span class="dot">·</span>{SITE.domain}</span>
        <h1 class="post-title">The hand at the keyboard.</h1>
        <p class="post-dek">
          Twenty years of shipping software, and a conviction that the parts worth writing
          down are the ones that don't change.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-rule"><span class="mark">§</span></div>

      <div class="post-body">
        <p>
          Hi — I'm <strong>Adam McCombs</strong>. I've spent a little over two decades building
          software, mostly as a full-stack engineer and, increasingly, as the person responsible
          for the engineers doing the building. I've written the feature, owned the on-call pager,
          made the architecture call that aged well, and made a few that didn't. This site is
          where I write down what survived.
        </p>
        <p>
          I work out of Austin, Texas. Over twenty-plus years I've watched a lot of stacks come
          and go — the language that was going to fix everything, the framework that was going to
          make the last one obsolete, the paradigm that turned out to be the previous paradigm in
          a new coat. What's struck me, again and again, is how little the <em>foundations</em>
          underneath all that churn actually move. That gap is the whole reason this exists.
        </p>

        <h2>Why I'm writing this</h2>
        <p>
          Most engineering writing optimizes for the surface — the tutorial, the changelog, the
          hot take with a half-life of a news cycle. Useful, but disposable. I wanted a place to
          argue the durable stuff from first principles: why an abstraction earns its keep, what
          correctness actually costs, how to read code as fast as you write it, where taste comes
          from when the rules run out. The kind of thing I wish someone had handed me three years
          in instead of a third framework to learn.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm not interested in being right about this quarter's tooling. I'm interested in the
          ideas that were true before it and will be true after it. Those are the ones that
          compound.
        </p>

        <h2>The detour that taught me the most</h2>
        <p>
          I didn't come up through a computer science pipeline. I came up through <em>music</em> —
          Texas State, ensembles, the marching band field at six in the morning, the kind of
          obsessive practice where you play the hard bar a hundred times until your hands stop
          asking your brain for permission. It turns out that's most of engineering, too:
          fundamentals drilled until they become reflex, individual craft folded into something
          that only works if the whole section is listening to each other. I've never really
          stopped thinking of good engineering as an ensemble problem.
        </p>

        <h2>What you'll get here</h2>
        <p>
          One essay every other week, sent through <a href={SITE.url}>the newsletter</a> — slow on
          purpose, free, and easy to leave. No framework tutorials, no churn. Just the foundations,
          argued honestly, by someone still doing the work. If that's your kind of reading, the
          form below is the whole pitch.
        </p>
        <p>
          And if you've got something to say on this subject yourself — I'm
          <a href="/write-for-us">looking for writers</a>.
        </p>

        <div class="post-end">❧</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <NewsletterCTA />
</BaseLayout>
